  "doi": "10.1074/jbc.m114.563502",
  "title": "A molecular basis for the interplay between T cells, viral mutants, and human leukocyte antigen micropolymorphism.",
  "journal": "The Journal of biological chemistry",
  "year": 2014,
  "authors": "Liu YC, Chen Z, Neller MA, Miles JJ, Purcell AW, McCluskey J, Burrows SR, Rossjohn J, Gras S."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined how a single HLA-B*35 polymorphism at two closely related alleles (HLA-B*35:01 and HLA-B*35:08) differentially presents an Epstein-Barr virus epitope (HPVGEADYFEY) and its naturally occurring variants, revealing the molecular basis for altered T cell receptor recognition. Mutations within the epitope at positions 4 and 5 differentially affected peptide flexibility and conformation when bound to each HLA variant, demonstrating how viral escape variants can shift their MHC restriction between nearly identical alleles. A single P5 substitution (Glu to Asp) remarkably reversed restriction preference from HLA-B*35:01 to HLA-B*35:08, illustrating how minimal viral mutations can exploit HLA micropolymorphism. This work explains the evolutionary interplay between HLA genetic diversity, TCR repertoire diversity, and viral mutation, showing how population-level HLA polymorphism constrains viral escape by ensuring that escape variants affecting one allele remain vulnerable to T cell recognition when presented on alternative HLA alleles.",
 "noncanonical": {
